title: "Evaluation Methodology — How We Measure, and How We Iterate"
description: "The full method behind sysf.io's small-model evaluations: a four-arm ablation scored deterministically with no LLM judge, RAG-aware fine-tuning, contamination control, and three published iterations across six Swiss legal domains — including the negative results."
tags: writing
resType: concept
resOrder: 0
date: 2026-07-21
kicker: Methodology
listTitle: "The evaluation methodology, in full — including what didn't work"
blurb: "A deterministic four-arm ablation, no LLM judge, RAG-aware fine-tuning, contamination control, Wilson intervals — and three iterations across six Swiss legal domains showing that task-matched data, not training budget, is what moves the number. The negative results are published too."
faq:
  - q: Why no LLM judge?
    a: "Because an LLM judge is another opaque model whose errors correlate with the model under test, and it can't be audited or reproduced. Every domain here numbers its legal units (article, or FINMA margin number Rz), so a citation is exactly checkable, and answers are string/number matched against a verified gold. Every figure is recomputed from frozen per-item run records — anyone can rerun the scorer and get the same numbers."
  - q: Isn't a 16–46 item eval set too small?
    a: "For an absolute leaderboard, yes — which is why we report 95% Wilson intervals and treat small-sample deltas as provisional. But for the *deltas between arms on the same set*, even a compact set is informative, and the method scales: the FINMA and OR sets are 183 and 172 items. Growing the smaller sets is the first item on the next iteration."
  - q: Do you publish results that got worse?
    a: "Yes. The second iteration regressed FINMA by 11.5 points and left OR flat; both are on this page and on their report pages. A methodology you can only trust when it flatters the vendor isn't a methodology."
