{% from "partials/components.njk" import sectionHead, faqList, cta %}

<section class="border-b border-ink-900/10 dark:border-white/10">
  <div class="container-x py-16 md:py-24">
    <p class="eyebrow">Concepts · Methodology</p>
    <h1 class="mt-4 max-w-4xl text-4xl font-bold leading-[1.08] tracking-tightest text-ink-900 md:text-5xl dark:text-white">
      How we measure — and how we iterate.
    </h1>
    <p class="mt-6 max-w-2xl text-lg prose-muted md:text-xl">
      The <a class="link-underline" href="/concepts/evaluation/">evaluation-first promise</a> is only as good as the machinery behind it. This is that machinery, in full: the scoring, the ablation, the fine-tuning, the contamination controls — and three published iterations across six Swiss legal domains, negative results included.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- The contract -->
<section class="container-x py-20 md:py-28">
  {{ sectionHead("The task", "Answer, and cite the exact rule.", "Every task is a short factual question about a Swiss legal text. A correct answer with a wrong citation is scored as a failure — because in regulated work it is one.") }}
  <div class="mt-10 grid gap-8 md:grid-cols-2">
    <div>
      <p class="prose-muted">A system must return exactly two lines:</p>
      <pre class="mt-4 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 bg-white p-5 font-mono text-sm text-ink-700 shadow-sm dark:border-white/10 dark:bg-ink-950 dark:text-ink-300">ANSWER: 30 Tage
SOURCE: DSG Art. 25</pre>
      <p class="mt-4 text-sm prose-muted">Two things are scored, both deterministically: is the answer correct, and did it cite the correct legal unit. The <strong class="text-ink-700 dark:text-ink-300">production bar is both at once</strong>.</p>
    </div>
    <div>
      <p class="prose-muted">Why the citation is not optional:</p>
      <p class="mt-4 text-sm prose-muted">A compliance officer asking "how long do we have to answer a data-subject access request?" needs <em>"Art. 25 DSG — 30 days"</em>, not a paragraph of confident prose. An assistant that answers correctly but cites the wrong article sends someone to the wrong rule. The citation is the difference between a defensible answer and a liability, so it is half the score.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- Four arms -->
<section class="border-y border-ink-900/10 bg-ink-900/[0.02] py-20 dark:border-white/10 dark:bg-white/[0.02] md:py-28">
  <div class="container-x">
    {{ sectionHead("The ablation", "Four systems, one open model.", "Same Apertus-8B, quantized identically to 4-bit, served identically. The only variables are retrieval and the fine-tune — so each isolates one mechanism.") }}
    <div class="mt-10 grid gap-5 md:grid-cols-4">
      {% set arms = [
        {k:"A", t:"Base", d:"The open model, as shipped."},
        {k:"B", t:"+ Retrieval", d:"Base model with BM25 over the corpus."},
        {k:"C", t:"Fine-tuned", d:"LoRA-tuned, no retrieval."},
        {k:"D", t:"Fine-tuned + retrieval", d:"The full system."}
      ] %}
      {% for a in arms %}
      <div class="rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm dark:border-white/10 dark:bg-ink-950 {{ 'ring-2 ring-red-500 ring-inset' if a.k == 'D' }}">
        <div class="font-mono text-sm text-swiss">{{ a.k }}</div>
        <h3 class="mt-2 text-base font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-white">{{ a.t }}</h3>
        <p class="mt-2 text-sm prose-muted">{{ a.d }}</p>
      </div>
      {% endfor %}
    </div>
    <p class="mt-6 max-w-2xl text-sm text-ink-500">A → B isolates retrieval; A → C isolates fine-tuning; the A/B/C/D square isolates their interaction. That interaction is usually the finding — the parts do not simply add.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- Scoring -->
<section class="container-x py-20 md:py-28">
  {{ sectionHead("Deterministic scoring", "No LLM judge, anywhere.", "The scorer is a few hundred lines of transparent code, not a model. Anyone can rerun it on the frozen records and get the same numbers.") }}
  <div class="mt-10 grid gap-5 md:grid-cols-3">
    {% set sc = [
      {t:"Answer", d:"Normalised string / number match against a verified gold answer, with per-item accepted variants (spelling, units, phrasings). Yes/no, numbers, durations, short phrases and small lists — machine-checkable by construction."},
      {t:"Citation", d:"Exact match of the legal unit — article number, or FINMA margin number (Rz) — against the gold, plus any explicitly listed adjacent unit. No partial credit."},
      {t:"Format, reported separately", d:"Strict two-line compliance is measured but never used to zero out a domain-correct answer, so the harness cannot inflate itself. Confidence: 95% Wilson intervals on every figure."}
    ] %}
    {% for s in sc %}
    <div class="rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 bg-white p-8 shadow-sm dark:border-white/10 dark:bg-ink-950">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-white">{{ s.t }}</h3>
      <p class="mt-2 text-sm prose-muted">{{ s.d }}</p>
    </div>
    {% endfor %}
  </div>
</section>

<!-- Corpus + retrieval + fine-tune -->
<section class="border-y border-ink-900/10 bg-ink-900/[0.02] py-20 dark:border-white/10 dark:bg-white/[0.02] md:py-28">
  <div class="container-x">
    {{ sectionHead("The pipeline", "Pinned data, transparent retrieval, RAG-aware fine-tuning.", "Every stage is reproducible from the repository.") }}
    <div class="mt-10 space-y-6 max-w-3xl">
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-white">Corpus</h3>
        <p class="mt-2 text-sm prose-muted">Pinned and SHA-256-checksummed from the official source — the Fedlex filestore for the five statutes, FINMA for the circulars. If the upstream text silently changes, the download fails loudly rather than corrupting the corpus. Text is chunked by legal unit (article, or margin number).</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-white">Retrieval</h3>
        <p class="mt-2 text-sm prose-muted">Plain BM25 (k=5) over the unit-chunked text — no embeddings, no external services, so the ranking is exactly reproducible. It is deliberately simple: the point is to measure what fine-tuning buys <em>on top of</em> honest retrieval, not to hide behind a clever retriever.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-white">RAG-aware fine-tuning</h3>
        <p class="mt-2 text-sm prose-muted">LoRA on Apertus-8B-Instruct, trained on the NVIDIA GB10 (DGX Spark) cluster, quantised to 4-bit with the same no-imatrix toolchain as the base arm to remove the quantiser as a confound. The key technique: each training example appears <strong class="text-ink-700 dark:text-ink-300">twice</strong> — once plain, once with retrieved context (gold unit guaranteed present). A model fine-tuned question-only <em>drops the citation line</em> when retrieval fills the context at inference; training the with-context form fixes that train/serve mismatch. It is why the fine-tune helps <em>with</em> retrieval instead of fighting it.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-white">Contamination control</h3>
        <p class="mt-2 text-sm prose-muted">Enforced in code, not by good intentions: any training item whose gold unit appears in the evaluation set is rejected, as is any near-duplicate question. The eval set is held fixed across every iteration, so a version-over-version delta is a real change, not an easier test.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- Iterations -->
<section class="container-x py-20 md:py-28">
  {{ sectionHead("Three iterations", "What we changed, and what it taught us.", "The same method, run three times across six domains. The instructive parts are the controls.") }}
  <div class="mt-10 space-y-8 max-w-3xl">
    <div class="rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 bg-white p-8 shadow-sm dark:border-white/10 dark:bg-ink-950">
      <div class="font-mono text-sm text-swiss">v1</div>
      <h3 class="mt-1 text-lg font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-white">Establish the ablation</h3>
      <p class="mt-2 text-sm prose-muted">BM25 k=5, LoRA r=16 / 3 epochs. Result across all six domains: retrieval is <em>necessary</em> (a small model cannot cite a unit it has never seen), and fine-tuning <em>on top of</em> retrieval (arm D) is the winning system, while fine-tuning <em>alone</em> (arm C) does not help and often regresses answer accuracy. For the four newer statutes the fine-tune data was weak — "topic identification" (which article covers which subject), not genuine question answering — which capped arm C.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 bg-white p-8 shadow-sm dark:border-white/10 dark:bg-ink-950">
      <div class="font-mono text-sm text-swiss">v2</div>
      <h3 class="mt-1 text-lg font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-white">Richer data — and a control</h3>
      <p class="mt-2 text-sm prose-muted">The four newer domains were retrained on <strong class="text-ink-700 dark:text-ink-300">genuine grounded factual Q&amp;A</strong>, authored per non-eval article and passed through a deterministic grounding filter (an answer is kept only if it is provably supported by its article's text — no LLM judge in the loop), growing the training set 1.4–3×. FINMA and OR already had human-verified Q&amp;A, so they got the opposite change as a control: <strong class="text-ink-700 dark:text-ink-300">only</strong> a capacity bump (r=32 / 4 epochs) on the <em>same</em> data.</p>
      <div class="mt-5 overflow-x-auto">
        <table class="w-full min-w-[560px] border-collapse text-sm">
          <thead><tr class="border-b border-ink-900/15 text-left dark:border-white/15">
            <th class="py-2 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-white">Domain (n)</th>
            <th class="py-2 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink-500">v2 lever</th>
            <th class="py-2 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink-500">Production bar (D) v1 → v2</th>
          </tr></thead>
          <tbody class="divide-y divide-ink-900/10 dark:divide-white/10">
            {% set r = [
              {d:"DSG (46)", l:"richer data", a:"54.3% → 82.6%", c:"text-swiss", g:"+28.3"},
              {d:"VVG (16)", l:"richer data", a:"37.5% → 56.2%", c:"text-swiss", g:"+18.7"},
              {d:"PrSG (20)", l:"richer data", a:"60.0% → 75.0%", c:"text-swiss", g:"+15.0"},
              {d:"HMG (22)", l:"richer data", a:"68.2% → 59.1%", c:"text-red-600", g:"−9.1"},
              {d:"FINMA (183)", l:"capacity only", a:"45.4% → 33.9%", c:"text-red-600", g:"−11.5"},
              {d:"OR (172)", l:"capacity only", a:"52.3% → 51.7%", c:"text-ink-500", g:"−0.6"}
            ] %}
            {% for x in r %}
            <tr>
              <td class="py-2 pr-4 font-medium text-ink-900 dark:text-white">{{ x.d }}</td>
              <td class="py-2 pr-4 prose-muted">{{ x.l }}</td>
              <td class="py-2 pr-4"><span class="text-ink-700 dark:text-ink-300">{{ x.a }}</span> <span class="font-mono {{ x.c }}">{{ x.g }}</span></td>
            </tr>
            {% endfor %}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p class="mt-5 text-sm prose-muted"><strong class="text-ink-900 dark:text-white">The finding: data beats capacity.</strong> Better task-matched data lifted the domains with room to improve; adding capacity to already-good data on the <em>same</em> examples over-fit (FINMA −11.5 at n=183). So v1 stays the published headline for FINMA/OR — v2 did not beat it, and we say so.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 bg-white p-8 shadow-sm dark:border-white/10 dark:bg-ink-950">
      <div class="font-mono text-sm text-swiss">v3</div>
      <h3 class="mt-1 text-lg font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-white">Isolate the lever, remove a free failure mode</h3>
      <p class="mt-2 text-sm prose-muted">v2 changed two things at once for the winners (richer data <em>and</em> r=32/4-epochs). v3 disentangles them: retrain the four data-domains at the lighter <strong class="text-ink-700 dark:text-ink-300">r=16 / 3 epochs</strong> on the same richer data, to confirm the gains are the data and to recover the capacity-driven citation dip on the already-strong domains. In parallel, output is generated under a <strong class="text-ink-700 dark:text-ink-300">formal grammar</strong> that constrains it to the two-line contract, removing malformed output as a failure mode for free. Diagnostics track the retrieval ceiling (how often the gold unit is actually in context) to tell whether remaining errors are the retriever's or the model's. <span class="text-ink-500">Results are being finalised and will appear on the per-domain report pages.</span></p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- Reproducibility -->
<section class="border-t border-ink-900/10 py-20 dark:border-white/10 md:py-28">
  <div class="container-x">
    {{ sectionHead("Why you can trust it", "Every number is falsifiable.", "This is the opposite of a benchmark you have to take on faith.") }}
    <div class="mt-10 max-w-3xl space-y-4 text-base prose-muted">
      <p><strong class="font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-white">Open harness, public data.</strong> The corpus is pinned public law; the harness — download, extraction, retrieval, scoring, training — is open at <a class="link-underline" href="https://github.com/chengmanov/apertus-swiss-eval" target="_blank" rel="noopener">github.com/chengmanov/apertus-swiss-eval</a>. In a Pilot the identical method runs on your documents, inside your environment, and the report stays yours.</p>
      <p><strong class="font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-white">Frozen records.</strong> Every arm writes a per-item record — prompt, raw response, parsed answer, retrieved units, pass/fail. Every headline number is recomputed from those records, so a scoring change applies retroactively and nothing is hand-entered.</p>
      <p><strong class="font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-white">Negative results published.</strong> The regressions are on the report pages next to the wins. The method is the product; the number is a floor, not a promise.</p>
    </div>
